# Enterprise Detection Engineering Lab (Windows + Sysmon)

---

## 🧠 Overview

This project is a hands-on Enterprise Detection Engineering Lab built using a Windows 11 virtual machine with Sysmon and Windows Security Event Logging enabled.

The goal of this lab is to simulate real-world Security Operations Center (SOC) workflows by generating endpoint telemetry, analyzing system behavior, and building security detections based on real Windows events.

This lab focuses on understanding how attackers generate activity on endpoints and how defenders detect, investigate, and map that behavior using industry-standard tools and frameworks.

---

## 🎯 Objectives

- Build a realistic Windows-based SOC detection lab
- Enable and analyze Sysmon telemetry
- Study Windows Security Event Logs
- Simulate user and process activity
- Build detection logic for endpoint behavior
- Understand attacker techniques through telemetry
- Map detections to MITRE ATT&CK framework

---

## 🧪 Lab Environment

- Windows 11 Virtual Machine (VMware Fusion)
- Sysmon (Sysinternals)
- Windows Event Viewer
- PowerShell & Command Prompt
- Windows Security Logs
- Isolated lab environment

---

## 📊 Telemetry Sources

### Windows Security Logs
- 4624 → Successful logon
- 4625 → Failed logon
- 4720 → User creation
- 4732 → Group membership change

### Sysmon Logs
- Event ID 1 → Process creation
- Event ID 3 → Network connections
- Event ID 7 → Image loading
- Event ID 10 → Process access
- Event ID 11 → File creation

